That's roughly 2× the effort of the monomorphized plan, and the proof is the one you'd actually want to cite.

Want me to proceed with this revised plan? Same questions still apply: branch name `verify/containers`, worktree at `../semi-persistent-containers-verus`, and I'd start by scaffolding the crate + getting `tagged.rs` through Verus on its own before touching anything storage-related.

Got it. Your point about the niche is exactly the thing that makes `Tagged` a real contract rather than a hand-wave. Let me record the design and start scaffolding.

## The `Tagged` contract, properly stated

The trait has two layers:

```rust
verus! {
pub trait Tagged: Sized + Copy {
    type Repr: Copy;

    // Layer 1: well-formed Repr values (the image of valid encodings)
    spec fn repr_wf(r: Self::Repr) -> bool;

    // Layer 2: the (value, tag) ↔ Repr bijection on well-formed Reprs
    spec fn value(r: Self::Repr) -> Self;
    spec fn tag(r: Self::Repr) -> bool;
    spec fn encode(v: Self, t: bool) -> Self::Repr;

    // Bijection axioms (proof obligations on every impl):
    proof fn encode_wf(v: Self, t: bool)
        ensures Self::repr_wf(Self::encode(v, t));

    proof fn encode_roundtrip(v: Self, t: bool)
        ensures Self::value(Self::encode(v, t)) == v,
                Self::tag(Self::encode(v, t)) == t;

    proof fn decode_roundtrip(r: Self::Repr)
        requires Self::repr_wf(r)
        ensures Self::encode(Self::value(r), Self::tag(r)) == r;

    // Exec methods (preserve repr_wf):
    exec fn into_repr(self) -> (r: Self::Repr)
        ensures r == Self::encode(self, false);

    exec fn from_repr(r: &Self::Repr) -> (v: Self)
        requires Self::repr_wf(*r)
        ensures v == Self::value(*r);

    exec fn set_tag(r: &mut Self::Repr)
        requires Self::repr_wf(*old(r))
        ensures *r == Self::encode(Self::value(*old(r)), true);

    exec fn clear_tag(r: &mut Self::Repr)
        requires Self::repr_wf(*old(r))
        ensures *r == Self::encode(Self::value(*old(r)), false);

    exec fn tag_of(r: &Self::Repr) -> (b: bool)
        requires Self::repr_wf(*r)
        ensures b == Self::tag(*r);
}
}
```

`repr_wf` is the niche obligation. For `DenseId<u32, 31 bits>` over `Repr = u32`, the proof discharges:

- `repr_wf(r) = true` (every `u32` is a valid encoding because the value-side has only 31 bits of range)
- `encode(v, t) = v.raw() | ((t as u32) << 31)` — well-defined because `v.raw() < 2^31` is part of `DenseId`'s invariant
- decode strips the high bit and reconstructs the `DenseId` from the low 31 bits

For a hypothetical `DenseId<u32, 32 bits>` (no spare bit) the proof would be unconstructible — exactly the right outcome.

For `BoolTagged<T>` where `T` has no niche, `Repr = (T, bool)` and the bijection is the identity. Proof is trivial; runtime cost is one extra bool per slot, paid honestly.

The `DenseId` trait gets a sibling obligation that exposes the bit budget:

```rust
pub trait DenseId: Copy {
    spec const VALUE_BITS: nat;
    proof fn fits_in_word(self) where ...
        ensures self.raw() < (1u64 << Self::VALUE_BITS);
}
```

Then "DenseId-with-bit-stealing" implies `Tagged` precisely when `VALUE_BITS < 8 * size_of::<Repr>()`. That implication is one lemma we prove once and reuse for every concrete `define_id31!` newtype.

**Crucially, none of this leaks into the deep-copy stack.** The ghost stack is `Seq<Seq<T>>`, never `Seq<Seq<T::Repr>>`. The `Tagged` machinery is invisible to the abstract spec — it's the implementation refinement that makes inline capture sound.

## `is_token_valid` as a checkable predicate

You're right that the existing code panics. We add a checked exec method that mirrors the ghost predicate, so callers have something to branch on:

```rust
exec fn is_token_valid(&self, t: VecToken) -> (b: bool)
    requires self.wf(),
    ensures b == self.fork_tree@.is_valid(t);
```

Callers can write:

```rust
if v.is_token_valid(token) {
    v.restore(token);   // precondition discharged by the if-guard
} else {
    // handle stale token
}
```

The existing `restore`'s precondition is `is_valid(t)`. If you skip the check and call `restore` on a stale token, Verus rejects the call statically. If you do the check first, the if-branch's path condition gives Verus the fact it needs.

We can additionally keep a `restore_unchecked` (or just `restore`) that assumes the precondition for hot paths where validity is statically obvious — no runtime check, no panic, identical codegen to today.

## Naming

Going with `containers-verus` for both the branch and the worktree directory (sibling of the main repo at `../containers-verus`). Slash-bearing names don't make great directory paths, and the existing `proof-search` precedent is in the same shape. If you'd rather have `verify-containers` or anything else, say so before I proceed and I'll adjust.

